+{"type":"message","id":"28c9d713","parentId":"c449a83a","timestamp":"2026-03-30T07:36:46.650Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Parent conversation handoff summary:\nParent conversation handoff summary\nSummary model: openai-codex/gpt-5.4-mini\nSource items: 431\n\nOverview:\nThe session identified a broad set of UI/backend bugs in the Weekly Commit app, then pivoted to preparing a Duet-style multi-step sweep to systematically search and fix them across the codebase. The core themes were: dark-mode contrast regressions from hard-coded neutral Tailwind classes, raw UUIDs leaking into user-facing views, week-selection state drifting between routes, and a few backend prompt/DTO completeness issues. A concrete Duet plan file was written to the repo root for an autonomous multi-step implementation run.\n\nSettled decisions:\n- Use Duet for the large bug sweep because it spans many files and layers (frontend + backend) and benefits from plan→implement→review cycles.\n- Keep the sweep focused on durable bug classes rather than one-off fixes: dark-mode neutral tokens, UUID display resolution, week-context synchronization, RCDO UX, and AI summary completeness.\n- Use the existing repo remote `https://labs.gauntletai.com/henrydegrasse/weekly-commit-module.git` for git operations; the previous changes were already committed and pushed as `fix(ui): role-based nav, week sync, dark-mode colors, UX polish` on `main`.\n- A Duet plan file was created at `duet-bug-sweep.md` in the repo root, intended for `/duet` → 'Implement from existing plan file'.\n- For Duet handoff, the recommended option is 'Include summary of current conversation' so agents get the design-system and UUID-display context.\n\nConstraints / must-remember items:\n- Do not modify `.pi/` contents or unrelated repo metadata during the sweep.\n- The project uses semantic color tokens for accessible dark mode; hard-coded `bg-neutral-*`/`text-neutral-*` surfaces should generally be replaced, except intentionally dark timeline marker colors (`bg-neutral-500+`) that already work in both modes.\n- Do not change public API contracts unless the plan explicitly includes the backend DTO change needed to support resolved-by display names.\n- The repository’s Duet config is fixed: static checks are `npm run check:static`, unit checks are `npm test`, with commit-per-step enabled.\n- The plan file deliberately scopes each step to a narrow set of files to avoid cross-layer drift and keep steps independently verifiable.\n- The current commit history and working tree contain many changes; the plan assumes follow-on autonomous work will search the whole codebase, but each step should only touch the files it owns.\n\nOpen questions:\n- Whether the Duet plan should be simplified before execution, since some steps are intentionally broad (e.g. sweeping remaining neutral classes across many components).\n- Whether additional UUID-display leaks exist outside the explicitly named Tickets, ExceptionQueue, and Notification surfaces.\n- Whether the Reconcile/Tickets route week-selection behavior actually needs changes or only a labeling/UX clarification after inspection.\n- Whether auto-activating newly created RCDO nodes is the right product behavior, or if an explicit user prompt/toast is preferable.\n- Whether any backend prompt/context fixes in ManagerAiSummaryService require additional test fixture updates beyond the plan’s scope.\n\nUse this handoff as background context. If it conflicts with the explicit task below or the current repository state, prioritize the explicit task and repo state.\n\nPlan overview:\n{\n  \"goal\": \"Systematic bug sweep across the Weekly Commit codebase (frontend + backend). Fix all remaining bg-neutral-* / text-neutral-* / bg-white dark-mode contrast violations, raw UUID input affordances, week-selection sync gaps, missing UX affordances, and minor logic gaps. The app is React/TypeScript + Spring Boot 3 / Java 21. The design system uses Tailw